    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "DTC Explanation: P0401"
    },
    {
      "type": "dtc",
      "code": "P0401",
      "text": "DTC P0401: EGR valve flow abnormality"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Detection principle explanation"
    },
    {
      "type": "figure",
      "asset": "2142_3.0_jpn_11259987_2.0_disp.png"
    },
    {
      "type": "figure",
      "asset": "2142_3.0_jpn_11231327_3.0_disp.png"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The EGR valve is controlled by the PGM-FI ECU; when the EGR valve opens, some of the exhaust gas flows through the exhaust gas recirculation system into the intake manifold. The exhaust gases mix with the air mixture and are then drawn into the combustion chamber to lower the combustion temperature and reduce NOx emissions. EGR valve flow failure is judged as follows. The EGR valve is fully closed during deceleration with the throttle valve fully closed. The PGM-FI ECU then opens the EGR valve fully; after a set time, the PGM-FI ECU detects fluctuations in intake manifold pressure when the EGR valve is fully opened to fully closed, and calculates the ratio of actual EGR flow to the normal EGR flow predicted by the PGM-FI ECU. If the ratio of the actual EGR flow rate is less than the set value, the PGM-FI ECU determines a failure and stores the DTC."
    },
